    "reasoning": "The requirement is to implement a finite state machine (FSM) that enables a shift register for exactly 4 clock cycles upon reset. The FSM needs to have a reset signal that is active high and synchronous to the clock. The design should assert shift_ena for 4 cycles immediately after reset and then remain low forever until reset occurs again. To achieve this, I will define four states: IDLE (default), ENABLE_1, ENABLE_2, and ENABLE_3. The state transitions will be handled in the next state logic, and the output will be enabled in states ENABLE_1, ENABLE_2, and ENABLE_3. A synchronous reset will set the FSM to ENABLE_1 state, and the counter of 4 cycles will be managed using the state sequence. I will declare all signals as logic and ensure proper initialization.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic reset,\n    output logic shift_ena\n);\n\n    // Define states using localparam\n    localparam IDLE      = 2'b00;\n    localparam ENABLE_1  = 2'b01;\n    localparam ENABLE_2  = 2'b10;\n    localparam ENABLE_3  = 2'b11;\n\n    // State register\n    logic [1:0] current_state, next_state;\n\n    // Sequential logic for state transition\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge reset) begin\n        if (reset)\n            current_state <= ENABLE_1;\n        else\n            current_state <= next_state;\n    end\n\n    // Next state logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        case (current_state)\n            ENABLE_1: next_state = ENABLE_2;\n            ENABLE_2: next_state = ENABLE_3;\n            ENABLE_3: next_state = IDLE;\n            default:  next_state = IDLE;\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Output logic\n    assign shift_ena = (current_state != IDLE);\n\nendmodule"
